1 Introduction

The data is taken from UCI. The data is related with direct marketing campaigns (phone calls) of a Portuguese banking institution. The classification goal is to predict if the client will subscribe a term deposit.

4 PreProcessing

Checked for null values, but no null values in data so we try and impute the unknown values in education using MICE

# Look for missing data
#There are no missing values in the dataset
sum(is.na(bank_db_full))
## [1] 0
#Multivariate Imputation by Chained Equations
summary(bank_db_full$education)
##   primary secondary  tertiary   unknown 
##      6851     23202     13301      1857
bank_db_full$education[bank_db_full$education=='unknown']<- NA

mice_mod <- mice(bank_db_full)

6 Prediction

Classification using various information gain based methods like decision tree, random forest. Evaluated the performance with respect to each other. Later used sampling with replacement to train the data in order to avoid bias of single label.

set.seed(100)
TrainData <- createDataPartition(y =bank_db_full$y , p=0.7, list = FALSE)
training <- bank_db_full[TrainData,]
testing <- bank_db_full[-TrainData,]
#Run some machine learning algorithms to evaluate which one works better with the training set.

#Random Forest

#Random forests are usually one of the two top performing algorithms along with boosting in prediction contests. 
#Lets evaluate its performance with the training data
objModel.RF <- randomForest(y ~ ., data=training)
show(objModel.RF)

#From both algorithms we can conclude that despite the total estimate error is acceptable we have high false negatives in the training set, 
#i.e. we are rejecting a high number of clients that will subscribe to the product offered. The problem lies in the highly unbalanced dataset in the response classes we want to classify. 
#This is the breakdown between responses in the original dataset
#A result of the nature of our data is that the classifier is biased towards the majority class.
#To penalize false positives and control the misclassification, we can up-sample the training dataset to get a more balanced dataset. 
#In theory this will allow us to control type I and type II errors. In order to improve further our results we can find the minimal number of trees that give us an acceptable error.
#By pruning the tree we will optimize it and avoid over-fitting of the model.

# sample the data to get a balanced dataset
trainingYes <- subset(training, y == "yes")
trainingNo <- subset(training, y == "no")
trainingSamplingYes <- trainingYes[sample(nrow(trainingYes), size = 5000, replace = TRUE),]
trainingSamplingNo <- trainingNo[sample(nrow(trainingNo), size = 5000, replace = TRUE),]
trainingSampling<- rbind.data.frame(trainingSamplingNo, trainingSamplingYes)

#As we got the lowest error with the tree algorithm we will follow these steps using the algorithm
objModelSampling.Tree <- tree(y~. ,trainingSampling, split = "gini")
summary(objModelSampling.Tree)
## 
## Classification tree:
## tree(formula = y ~ ., data = trainingSampling, split = "gini")
## Number of terminal nodes:  648 
## Residual mean deviance:  0.2802 = 2620 / 9352 
## Misclassification error rate: 0.0691 = 691 / 10000
tree.trainmodelpredSampling <- predict(objModelSampling.Tree, type = 'class')
results <- table(tree.trainmodelpredSampling, trainingSampling$y)


#The false positives are
percent(results[2] / (results[1] + results[2]))
## [1] "7.74%"
#The false negatives
percent(results[3] / (results[3] + results[4]))
## [1] "6.08%"
confusionMatrix(tree.trainmodelpredSampling, trainingSampling$y)
